          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": ", pillaging the country and ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "children": [
              {
                "detail": 0,
                "format": 0,
                "mode": "normal",
                "style": "",
                "text": "scorching the earth",
                "type": "text",
                "version": 1
              }
            ],
            "direction": "ltr",
            "format": "",
            "indent": 0,
            "type": "link",
            "rel": null,
            "target": null,
            "title": null,
            "url": "/the-war-against-the-climate-movement/",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": ".",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "They got off scot free after the financial crisis, they got off scot free as they’ve pandemic profiteered, they got off scot free last night in a debate that mostly refused to focus on the material well being of millions of people, and they are getting off scot free this morning as the debate analysis revolves around decorum.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "This isn’t some accident. The hollowing out of our politics is the outcome of a system designed to produce a particular result. Corporate-bankrolled politicians and millionaires paid by billionaires that you watch on your cable TV roundtables have no interest in scrutinizing, challenging or focusing the political conversation on the power of billionaires and corporations — even though that plutocratic power is the central problem destroying the country and the world.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "As an investigative journalist who focuses on following the money and digging through documents, I always find this time of year to be the most depressing and most challenging to the point where I start questioning whether any of the painstaking work of reporting, digging and exposing even matters.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Even more than other moments in our dumbed-down democracy, election season feels like the time that nobody wants to focus on literally anything other than rooting for their home team — issues, crimes and policy outcomes be damned. Having worked on many campaigns, I understand that some of this is the natural ebb and flow of politics, but a lot it is unnatural. In the last decade, each election season — regardless of outcome — has felt like another step in a nihilistic devolution, and last night felt like a giant leap.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "In a country whose presidential debates are often lazy and dumb, this debate seemed like a spectacle that was aggressively and deliberately stupid — as if the entire event was designed for the purpose of being an infuriating distraction from stuff like corruption, corporate power and the brutal class war being waged by the oligarchy.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "In a sense, distraction was almost certainly Trump’s strategy because his record and policies give him very little to brag about. And the debate format, the punditry, the horse race coverage and the media conversation — the Narrative, as it were — are now perfectly calibrated to give Trump exactly the kind of circus that he wants and that America’s cable-TV-addled psyche responds to.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Rather than the political process being a forum to seriously litigate things like inequality and ecocide, the election is a pro-wrestling match that holds itself out as an infotainment escape from those emergencies. In a pundit-driven political culture that values Winning The Day In Politics over anything else, the material concerns of ordinary Americans do not seem to matter at all.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "And yet, in the real world, these crises actually do matter — and they aren’t being put on hold or going away just because the election won’t focus on them. They aren’t going away because the corporate media doesn’t care about them. And they aren’t going away because our presidential debates are now just three dudes yelling at each other.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "These emergencies keep getting more intense — and if we don’t use what power we have in our tattered democracy to address them, then that downward trajectory will continue. If nothing fundamentally changes, then everything will fundamentally change for the worse.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Keep that in mind after this horrible election is over — because that’s not the end of the struggle, it’s only the end of the beginning.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
